snippet: Within hours of reports that Mohamed ElBaradei had been chosen as prime minister, Egypt’s powerful ultraconservative Islamist party said it would refuse to work with him.
abstract: Egypt's new leaders struggle to put together new government; disagreements over who should be interim prime minister spill into public view and showcase divisions among those who endorsed overthrow of Pres Mohamed Morsi, country's first democratically elected president; Nobel Prize-winning diplomat Mohamed ElBaradei is initially reported as prime minister, but ultraconservative Islamist party Al Nour refuses to work with him because of his liberal views.
lead_paragraph: Within hours of reports that Mohamed ElBaradei had been chosen as prime minister, Egypt’s powerful ultraconservative Islamist party said it would refuse to work with him.
